  "summary": "In a room in Dover, Theo and Richard engage in a tense confrontation regarding a recent event involving Vincent Easton. Theo accuses Richard of scheming for her to meet Easton alone at night, dressed in a specific way, in the hope that Easton would make a deal for certain files. She realizes Richard was willing to sacrifice her reputation to protect his own interests and safety. Theo reveals that she had actually left with Vincent Easton three days prior, contrary to the story the servants told Richard about her going to the countryside. Although Richard attempts to forgive her, Theo refuses, citing his own infidelity and his recent betrayal. She declares she is leaving for her freedom and exits the house.\n\nIn a separate scene, a man in a dark coat arrives at a residence on Calver Street during cold, snowy weather. He asks Mrs. Casey for \"Madame Lion\" and whistles the tune of \"Three Blind Mice\" as he ascends the stairs.\n\nMeanwhile, Molly Davis observes a new sign for \"Monksville Manor Guest House.\" She reflects on her husband Jiles's talents as they prepare for their new venture. Following the death of Aunt Katherine, Molly inherited Monkswell Manor. Because the couple could not find a smaller residence and struggled with the bulky Victorian furniture, they decided to run the manor as a guesthouse. A lawyer notes that the house is in good condition due to extensive renovations performed by the late Miss Emery before the war.",
